              <div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'll do the second half of the batch next weekend, but in the mean time I've acquired some SAF-05, so it will be interesting to see how much of a difference the yeast makes.</div><br /><br />that's awesome; I've been toying with the idea of experimenting with splitting batches and comparing yeasts, but the time and space is just too much right now.  <br /><br />I bottled my first 5-gallon batch last night.  (Bavarian wheat)<br />-having an autosiphon to transfer from the fermentor into the bottling bucket is a must!  I cut the hose too short though; It was an unwieldy 10' so I hacked it into (2) 4' pieces and a 2' piece. I think 6-7' would be perfect to allow me to rack from the fermenter on a table to the bottling bucket on the floor.  I need a clip to hold the hose too.  <br />-I used about 18&quot; of hose between the bottling bucket and the bottling wand; I think it should either be about 10&quot; (so that it hangs straight down) or 24-30&quot; (so that I can actually move it around).<br />-wine thief is a great tool for taking hydrometer readings<br />-I only ended up with ~4.25 gallons; I'll have to review my process.  I think I lost more than expected in the boil.  I neglected to check OG, so I'm not sure.  <br /><br /><br />Next up is a small (2 gallon) batch of cider; I'm just going to kind of wing that one.  I also have an ingredient kit for a bavarian grand cru, but I'd like to hold off on that until I get my wort chiller together and retrieve the propane burner so that I can do full boils.  <br /><br />what do you people use for make-up water?  I've been using the Poland spring 2.5-gallon jugs but I think I'm going to start getting 5-gallon jugs.  The water in my apartment is crap and I don't feel like running 5 or 6 gallons through my pitcher filter for every batch.

              

              
              
