          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Eh, my first half-dozen or so batches were extract brews fermented at around 72-75 and they turned out decent.  I was using quality LME from Northern Brewer and Austin Homebrew (theirs is the best I've seen), though.  That's the main problem with Mr. Beer kits -- crappy malt extract.  I don't know what type of yeast they use but that's probably not the culprit.  You may get some off flavors fermenting at higher temperatures but they should be minor and will probably dissipate with aging.  Vinegar is not going to happen unless you get an infection.<br /><br />Before I discovered that our local water is terrible for brewing (very high in bicarbonates, but feels &quot;soft&quot; due to almost no calcium) I had to age my beer for three months after bottling before it got good.  After that it was great!

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
