              I'm planning out my next batch (won't be able to make it for another couple of weeks), and I'd like some feedback/advice.  I'm aiming for a lighter, easy drinking beer that will be ready fairly quickly for summertime refreshment.  I'd prefer not to have a heavily hopped beer (so no IPAs for this one) to keep the audience appeal broad.  <br /><br />I'm thinking of either this Honey Ale<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.midwestsupplies.com/homebrewing-ingredients/recipe-kits/honey-bee-ale.html">http://www.midwestsupplies.com/homebrew ... e-ale.html</a><!-- m --><br /><br />or failing that, this Cream Ale<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.midwestsupplies.com/liberty-cream-ale.html">http://www.midwestsupplies.com/liberty-cream-ale.html</a><!-- m --><br /><br />I have a soft spot for the Honey Ale since the Leinenkugel Honeyweiss was my go-to summer beer for a while, and I'd like to brew something similar.  Has anyone had any experience doing something like this?  Not quite a mead, but not quite a traditional ale either?  Concerns I have:<br /><br />-From the reviews, I'm wondering if it will really be in top form during the summer, or if it will hit it's peak closer to the Fall.  It might be ready as early as the first part of July if it really does mature quickly, but it might also take until mid-August.<br /><br />-I would probably follow the advice to not add the honey until the last 10-15 minutes of the boil to make sure the honey flavor comes through.  The reviews are somewhat conflicting over just how much of a honey flavor I would get from early vs late addition.<br /><br />-I'm also concerned with making this not quite so hoppy.  I would be using the pellets in a nylon bag, and probably following the recommended timings (60 minutes for Tettnang, 5 minutes for Vanguard).  Anyone have experience on how that would turn out?  Would I want to dial it down a bit to keep it sweeter?<br /><br />If a honey ale is not a good idea, I'll probably go with the cream ale instead, but I'm interested in hearing from anyone who has done a honey ale, particularly if you've done this kit from Midwest.<br /><br />-

              

              
              
            </div>
